node.text: Few people have lost as much money as quickly as Bill Hwang. In March, the previously unknown Wall Street whale and his family firm, Archegos, triggered losses of more than $20 billion in just two days. The result was one of the most spectacular implosions in modern financial history. (via @businessweek)

node.title: How Archegos Capital Cost Wall Street $20 Billion

node.text:
In almost every way measurable, millennials in the U.S. at 40 are doing worse financially than the generations that came before them.

Fewer millennials own homes than their parents did at their age. They have more debt — especially student debt. They simply aren’t as wealthy. 

Now, if predictions of a long, post-Covid economic boom are to be believed, this may be the last opportunity an entire generation has to build wealth before heading off into retirement.

node.title: Millennials Are Running Out of Time to Build Wealth to Retire

node.text: Few people have lost as much money as quickly as Bill Hwang. In March, the previously unknown Wall Street whale and his family firm, Archegos, triggered losses of more than $20 billion in just two days. The result was one of the most spectacular implosions in modern financial history. (via @businessweek)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on August 14, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, food, indoor and text that says 'The best new restaurantsin New York, as chosen by top chefs Jae Jung Bloomberg'.

node.text:
Over the last year and a half almost every dining establishment in New York has had to scramble to stay in business, deploying takeout menus and outdoor seating areas to survive.

Now things are finally turning a corner, and life has returned to the city — and its restaurant scene.

We asked 14 chefs from around the New York area to shout out their favorite places that have opened since the beginning of the year. Tap the link in our bio to see the recommendations.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on August 14, 2021. May be an image of tree, outdoors and text that says 'Want tosell your mansion fast? Make sureit's move-in ready Bloomberg'.

node.text:
The luxury real estate market is in uncharted territory. The city was dead, then it was red-hot. Sales in the suburbs were manic, and now numbers are contracting. Vacation homes are now for living in year-round, but also, the Hamptons have returned to a seasonal cycle.

It’s a headache for buyers — and a nightmare for sellers. For homeowners seeking a quick deal, making properties move-in ready is key, according to Corcoran CEO Pamela Liebman.

“Right now it’s really hard to renovate a house,” she says. “So if you have a house that’s ready to go, we’re seeing a definite premium on that,” Read more at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Bloomberg Business on August 14, 2021 tagging @businessweek. May be an image of text that says 'Apple's new phones show how it's perfected the lucrative game of inches Bloomberg'.

node.text:
For all the technological wizardry, iPhone camera and chip improvements can seem a little uninspiring. The real magic is their effect on Apple’s earnings.

Unlike innovations such as Face ID, the chip and camera improvements bring a dual benefit to the Cupertino-based company: Not only do consumers pay a premium for the new features, they also usually end up needing more storage to make the most of the new toys.

Storage, it turns out, is an unbelievable money-printing machine. In fact, it might even be Apple’s secret weapon. Tap the link in our bio for more. (via @businessweek)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Bloomberg Business on August 14, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, eyeglasses and text that says 'The new rich are overtaking old money in Korea's billionaire ranks BI omberg'.

node.text:
Self-made billionaires are shooting up the wealth rankings in South Korea, overtaking the families behind the country’s decades-old sprawling conglomerates known as “chaebol.”

Brian Kim, the founder of mobile-messaging app Kakao, is the most prominent example with a fortune of $12.9 billion, who recently replaced Samsung heir Jay Y. Lee as the nation’s richest person.

Some of the newly minted wealthy are getting into philanthropy. Kakao’s Brian Kim and Kim Bong-jin, the founder of food-delivery app Woowa Brothers, have pledged to give away their personal fortunes. Tap the link in bio to read more about Korea's newest billionaires.

node.text:
The delta variant is shifting the financial landscape. If you’re lucky enough to have money to invest, where should you put it?
 
We asked our panel of six experts for tips on the best bets as the recovery evolves. Their ideas range from Chinese power companies, to healthcare stocks, to newly reopened hedge funds — or, in one case, a splurge on an electric motorbike.

Tap the link in our bio for our updated guide.

📷: Scott Olson/Getty Images

node.text:
Six thousand miles from Wall Street, in the ancient Silk Road city of Almaty, lies the private retreat of a little-known financial empire.

Freedom Holding Corp.’s share price has soared 500% over the past couple of years. Its billionaire founder, Timur Turlov, says he’s built his fortune giving rich Russians, Kazakhs, Uzbeks and Ukrainians a piece of the Wall Street action.

According to Freedom’s marketing materials, its clients have gotten in on more than 100 U.S. IPOs since 2020, from Airbnb to Bumble — a level of access small brokers actually based in the U.S. can only dream of. The question is, how? Tap the link in our bio for the full story.

node.text:
Amazon Studios is relocating the Lord of the Rings universe to Britain.

New Zealand’s dramatic landscapes formed the backdrop for the movie franchise based on the fantasy novels. The first season of Amazon’s adaptation was filmed there too, but it plans to shift production of the second. 

Amazon says the move is part of a strategy of expanding its footprint in the U.K., though industry publication Deadline said New Zealand’s border closures had prevented British cast members from traveling home and Amazon execs from visiting sets. Read more via the link in our bio.

📷: New Line Cinema

New Zealand’s borders will remain closed until 2022, with a cautious reopening starting in the new year, Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern said.
 
The country has completely stamped out coronavirus and largely returned to life as normal. Ardern said New Zealand will complete its vaccine rollout — which is proceeding much more slowly than in places like the U.S. and the U.K. — before allowing international travelers to return. 

Read in full at the link in our bio. (via @quicktake)

node.text:
Britney Spears' father said in a court filing Thursday he plans to exit the conservatorship that has controlled her life and money for 13 years.

The documents said James Spears would resign from his role once several lingering issues are resolved, and he "continues to serve dutifully" in the meantime.

Though the filing gave no timetable for his departure, it was celebrated as a victory by fans in the #FreeBritney movement. Full story at the link in bio.

📷: Valerie Macon/AFP via Getty Images

node.text:
U.S. regulators approved giving a third Covid vaccine dose to some high-risk groups in an effort to improve protection for those with impaired responses to standard shots.

The authorization applies to both Moderna and Pfizer, and covers organ transplant recipients as well as other vulnerable patients.

Bolstering the agency’s move was a study published in the New England Journal of Medicine showing that an extra dose of Moderna’s vaccine significantly raised antibody levels against Covid in transplant patients. Tap the link in bio to read more.

node.text:
The number of people of color in the U.S. is growing, pointing toward a future in which the country is majority non-White. The number of people who identify as more than one race increased 276%, reaching 33.8 million in 2020 from 9 million in 2010.

The White population, while still a majority, decreased 8.6%. The Latino population -- which the Census asks about separately from race -- grew 23%. The Asian population grew 35.5%, and the African American population grew 5.6%.“

As the country has grown, we have continued to evolve in how we measure the race and ethnicity of the people who live here,” said Nicholas Jones, the bureau’s director and senior adviser for race and ethnicity research.

Read more about the survey at the link in our bio.
